ref="https://fediverse-webring-enthusiasts.glitch.me/profiles/shellsharks_infosec.exchange/index.html" target="_blank"><i class="ph ph-circle"></i> Webring Enthusiasts</a><li><a href="https://fedia.io/m/cybersecurity" target="_blank"><i class="ph ph-square-half"></i> Fedia.io</a></ul></nav><main class="container_item"><div class="pageheader"></div><article class="post h-entry"><header class="post-header"><h1 class="post-title p-name" id="title" style="display:inline;">HIRING::::URGENT!::SECURITYSPECIALIST:::REMOTE</h1><span style="color:#CA3342;font-size:4em;line-height: 20px;">.</span></header><div class="primarycolor" style="font-style:italic; font-size:150%; font-weight:15px; position:relative;">Roasting recruiter emails</div><!--<div id="postinfo"> <span class="time"><i class="ph ph-note-pencil"></i> by <span class="hov p-author h-card">Mike Sass</span> <a href="/about" rel="author"><img class="u-photo" src="https://shellsharks-images.s3.amazonaws.com/surfshark.png" style="display:inline; height:1em;" /></a></span><br/> <br/> <span class="categories"> &raquo; technology, blog </span></div>--><div class="post-content e-content" style="margin-top: 30px;"><p>If you are in the tech space, you are probably accustomed to the daily barrage of poorly formatted and eye-gougingly styled job emails from tiny recruitment shops. What is up with those? Why are they so bad?<p>Take for example, what you see below‚Ä¶<p><br /><p><img src="https://shellsharks-images.s3.amazonaws.com/2024/bizarre_recruiters.jpg" alt="HIRING:::::URGENT::::SECURITYSPECIALIST::::REMOTE!!" /><p><br /><p><em>OK</em>, yeah‚Ä¶ <em>wow</em>. Rough on the eyes right? To be transparent, this is NOT an actual email I‚Äôve received, it is instead something I crafted where every bizarre formatting, style and language choice was taken directly from, or heavily inspired by, an email I <em>have</em> received in literally the past 3 days or so. I‚Äôve just decided to mush all of these oddities into a single email for comedic effect. So let‚Äôs go ahead and roast it a bit‚Ä¶<ul><li>Too often they‚Äôre either not bothered to address the email to me, get my name wrong or have something generic like ‚ÄúCANDIDATE‚Äù.<li>Weird ellipses in places they‚Äôre not called for.<li>2+ exclamation points in random places.<li>Things are just highlighted at random, often with different colors throughout. Oh and the dark mode version of these emails is even MORE illegible.<li>Multiple font types, font sizes, line spacing, font weights, you name it‚Ä¶<li>Crazy amount of white space inbetween sections.<li>Plenty of language follies. (<em>I really mean no offense here to non-native English speakers. I understand the difficulty of learning a second language, but in a setting where you are catering to an english-speaking candidate pool, getting this right could go a long way in making these emails seem more legitimate &amp; professional</em>)<ul><li>‚Äú<em>I came to you regarding one of my job position</em>‚Äù<li>‚Äú<em>We are looking for Engineer Please review below job description</em>‚Äù<li>‚Äú<em>If you are interested then please share me your resume</em>‚Äù</ul><li>Text is tabbed out in random ways.<li>Table like formatting with incredibly inconsistent margins.<li>‚ÄúRemote‚Äù roles that are also onsite?<li>Scary bolded red lines for VISA requirements.<li>Section headers are inconsistently styled.<li>Lists with bullets, lists without bullets, lists with two different kinds of bullets, blank list items.<li>Whatever this is ‚Äì&gt; ‚Äú<em>??????Required????5?????Years</em>‚Äù, at the end of list items.<li>and ya gotta love those signature blocks.</ul><p>I don‚Äôt want this ‚Äúroast‚Äù to come off as mean-spirited. Having actually worked with some of the folks behind these emails, I can assure you that they are in many cases, real people, real recruiters, recruiting for real jobs at real companies. They are, like the rest of us, trying to make a go of this crazy world.<p><em>But!</em> It‚Äôs wild to me that these emails get crafted, whether by hand or by some cursed automation somewhere and then sent, likely en-masse, to people like myself in the hopes that we‚Äôll be encouraged to respond. I suppose if you‚Äôre out-of-work or dangerously curious (as I often am) you‚Äôre willing to entertain even the wackiest of job propositions. These just straight-up don‚Äôt pass the eye test though. Since I know for a <em>fact</em> that there is some subset of these emails that are legitimate, they <em>must</em> be interested in improving their response rate for potential candidates right? As such, it wouldn‚Äôt take much to clean these up and make them A LOT more palatable. So why do they continue to look like this? Is no one helping them? Do they have individuals who work at these companies who <em>actually</em> look at these emails, then just nod and say ‚Äúlooks good to me!‚Äù?<p>So here‚Äôs my plea to these recruiting agencies. Pick a font. ONE FONT. Pick a font size. No highlighting. Easy on the white space. Stop capitalizing things at random. Simple sections with bulleted lists is fine! Proofread, just a little. Make sure you get my name right, or a simple - <em>NORMAL!</em> - greeting is fine (e.g. ‚ÄúHello‚Äù). I <em>promise</em> this will improve take rate, and spare my eyes a bit in the process.<p>Thanks for reading!</div></article><hr class="fin"><div id="poststats" class="containbox" style="margin: auto;"> <span class="time"><i class="ph ph-calendar-dot"></i> Published: <span class="dt-published">May 3, 2024</span></span> <a class="u-url u-uid" href></a><br> <span class="categories"><i class="ph ph-tag"></i> Tags: <span class="primarybg" style="border-radius:15px;padding:0px 5px 0px 5px;"><a class="p-category" href="/tags?tag=technology">#technology</a></span> <span class="primarybg" style="border-radius:15px;padding:0px 5px 0px 5px;"><a class="p-category" href="/tags?tag=funny">#funny</a></span> <span class="primarybg" style="border-radius:15px;padding:0px 